## Context

GSD's `pause-work` writes a `.continue-here.md` checkpoint mid-phase (current step,
decisions made, next action). `resume-work` reads it and restores context. This
handles the case: "I'm halfway through step 3 of 7, session ends unexpectedly."

IDH has `end-session` (day wrap, natural break point) and `/perch` (read-only
orientation). Neither writes a mid-execution checkpoint. Recovery relies on reading
STATE.md and git log, which covers orientation but not fine-grained resume.

A possible IDH version: `perch --save` writes to `.git/session-state.md`
(local-only, like `.wip` files). `/perch` without `--save` continues to be
read-only.

## Question

Does IDH actually lose work due to lack of mid-session checkpoints? The case
arises when: (a) context compaction happens mid-task, or (b) session is interrupted.
Context compaction already preserves modified files + test commands (per workflow.md).
So the gap may be narrow. Develop by usage: wait for a real incident before building.
